The fragility of a flat world
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman said so. Friedman chose this provocative title for his bestseller to make people aware of the astonishing impact of technology on the world economy.
Distances are shortening.
Geographic barriers can no longer provide easy security.
European and American manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals are both facing the challenge of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they talk to are likely to be in India.
Skeptics point out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As some people say, the world is not flat but "hilly".
The contour map of global economic activities shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of scarcity.
Not only that, distance still has a long way to go before it loses its effect.
Even in neighboring countries with relatively low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the US, domestic trade far exceeds cross-border trade.
The geographical distance between Seattle and Vancouver is close, but Vancouver's trade with more distant Toronto is much higher than with neighboring Seattle.
Despite such criticism, Friedman still put forward an important point.
Globalization can be defined as interdependence between different continents, its history as old as human history, witnessing the migration of races and religions, and also witnessing the ancient trade along the Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different, with a faster pace and a deeper level of integration.
After the first transatlantic telegraph cable was laid in 1868, Europeans and Americans could communicate with each other in just a minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes described a British person living in London who could order goods from all over the world by phone and have them delivered at home in the afternoon.
However, Keynes' British person was an exception of great wealth.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy goods from all over the world at their local supermarkets.
Similar to this, 20 years ago, there was immediate global communication, but it was beyond the economic reach of most people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an internet cafe and acquire capabilities that were previously only within the grasp of governments, multinational corporations, and a few individuals or institutions with large budgets.
The significant drop in computing, communication, and transportation costs has made technology more widespread.
Just 10 years ago, two-thirds of internet users were still concentrated in the United States.
Today, the proportion of internet users in the United States is less than a quarter of the global total.
Knowledge is power, and the number of people who possess information today has set a record high in human history.
Nongovernmental organizations now possess capabilities that were previously only within the grasp of governments.
The status of nation-states as global political actors will not change temporarily, but they must learn to share this vast stage with more participants, including institutions like the Oxford Famine Relief Committee, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like al-Qaeda.
However, this flattening process is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred in the past.
The world economy was highly integrated in 1914, but over the next 30 years, the interdependence of countries in the economy continued to decline.
It wasn't until 1970 that the global economy recovered to the level of integration it had once had, and even then, it was still separated by the Iron Curtain.
World War I was the catalyst for the reversal, and during the two world wars and the Cold War, people witnessed a decline in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization.
This reflected the deeper problems of domestic inequality caused by economic development in the 19th century.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, and the result was the abnormal development of ideologies such as fascism and communism, which led to the fragmentation of nations and the world.
After World War II, the welfare state system in the West provided a safety net for people who were harmed by economic change, encouraging them to accept the benefits of international economic interdependence.
Some analysts believe that China's role today is very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic inequality, constantly moving towards nationalism, challenging the dominant powers, and ultimately triggering a world war that reverses the progress of economic globalization.
Although the US and Chinese economies are highly interdependent today, the economies of Britain and Germany were just as interconnected before 1914.
However, this reasoning is not complete.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had surpassed that of Britain.
However, even if China maintains its current high growth rate, its economy is unlikely to catch up with that of the US within at least 20 years.
The greater threat to the flat world is more likely to come from non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in a surprise attack than the Japanese government did at Pearl Harbor in 1941.
I call this phenomenon the privatization of war.
If such forces were to acquire nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo a revolutionary change.
At that time, it would become even more difficult for people and goods to cross borders.
If the aforementioned forces were to destroy the oil output in the Persian Gulf, which accounts for two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic downturn like that of the 1930s could further strengthen the forces of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two driving forces of globalization.
So far, policies have further solidified the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken a leading role in promoting policies to eliminate obstacles.
However, the events described above may reverse this policy.
Some critics of globalization may even wish to see such a result.
But such a result, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst-case scenario in both fields - the reversal of the economic globalization trend of spreading technology and power, along with the further solidification of the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization, such as wars, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If this were to happen, the flat world would become a desert.
